null-auf-tempo-100-3753077.html#bild30</ref>\n|\n|-\n|[[BMW M5|BMW M5 Competition]]\n|{{cvt|460|kW|hp PS|0}}\n|2018\n|{{nts|2.9}} sec<ref name=\"AZ3\"/>\n|Front-engine, with 5 seats\n|-\n|[[Ferrari 488 Pista]]\n|{{cvt|530|kW|hp PS}}\n|2018\n|{{nts|2.9}} sec<ref name=\"AMS\">https://www.auto-motor-und-sport.de/sportwagen/leistungs-beschleunigungswerte-sportwagen-0-100-km-h/#bildergalerie</ref>\n|\n|-\n|[[Tesla Model S]] Performance Ludicrous\n|{{cvt|611|PS|kW hp PS|order=out}}\n|2019\n|{{nts|2.9}} sec<ref name=\"AZ3\"/>\n|All-electric\n|-\n|[[McLaren 650S#675LT (2015\u2013)|McLaren 675LT]]\n|{{cvt|675|PS|kW hp PS|order=out}}\n|2015\n|{{nts|3.0}} sec<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.auto-motor-und-sport.de/test/mclaren-675lt/|title=MCLAREN 675LT IM TEST|first=Christian|last=Gebhardt|website=[[Auto Motor und Sport]]|language=de|date=2015-08-21|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|Limited to 1000 produced{{efn-lr|name=675LT|including Coup\u00e9 and Spider combined}}\n|-\n|[[Ferrari 812 Superfast]]\n|{{cvt|800|PS|kW hp PS|0|order=out}}\n|2017\n|{{nts|3.0}} sec<ref>Auto Bild Sportscars 10/2018</ref>\n|Front-engine\n|-\n|[[Mercedes-AMG GT 4-Door Coup\u00e9|Mercedes-AMG GT 63 S 4MATIC+]]\n|{{cvt|470|kW|hp PS|0}}\n|2018\n|{{nts|3.0}} sec<ref>Auto Bild Sportscars 2/2020</ref><ref>https://www.autobild.de/artikel/mercedes-amg-gt-63-s-4matic-test-14368661.html</ref>\n|4-door Coup\u00e9\n|-\n|[[Nissan GT-R#GT-R NISMO|Nissan GT-R NISMO]]\n|{{cvt|441|kW|hp PS}}\n|2018\n|{{nts|3.0}} sec<ref>https://www.autozeitung.de/nissan-gt-r-nismo-test-194580.html</ref>\n|Front-engine\n|-\n|}\n\n==Table notes==\n{{notelist-lr|30em}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of fastest production cars]]\n{{portalbar|Cars|Technology|Lists}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{Extreme motion}}\n\n[[Category:Car performance]]\n[[Category:Lists of cars|fastest]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\nThis list is limited to unmodified [[production car]]s which meet the eligibility criteria below. All entries must be able to be verified from reliable sources.\n\n==Eligible cars==\n{{Further|List of automotive superlatives|List of fastest production cars#Notes for editors|Production car}}\nBecause of the inconsistencies with the various definitions of production cars, dubious claims by manufacturers and self-interest groups, and inconsistent or changing application of the definitions, this list has a defined set of requirements. For further explanation of how these were arrived at see the links above.\n\n===Production car definition===\nFor the purposes of this list a production car is defined as:\n\n# Being constructed principally for retail sale to consumers for their personal use, and to transport people on public roads (no commercial or industrial vehicles are eligible);\n# Fitted with the original manufacturer-supplied road tires;\n# Having had 25 or more instances made by the original vehicle manufacturer and offered for commercial sale to the public in new condition (cars modified by either professional tuners or individuals are not eligible);\n# Being [[Street-legal vehicle|street-legal]] in their intended markets and capable of passing any official tests or inspections required to be granted this status.\n\n===Further limitations===\nFor the purpose of manageability, this list is limited to production cars that are able to reach 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h time or 0\u201360&nbsp;mph (0\u201397&nbsp;km/h) in 3.0 seconds or less for the first list or cover a quarter-mile (402&nbsp;m) from a standing start in 11.0 seconds or less for the second list.\n\n== By 0\u201360 mph (0\u201397&nbsp;km/h) time (3.0 seconds or less) ==\n\nIf an independent time becomes available, that time will be listed over the manufacturer's time regardless if the latter is quicker. Many elements change how fast the car can accelerate to {{convert|60|mph|abbr=on|order=flip}}.{{efn-lr|name=Basis|Various factors can contribute to variability in car speed test results. British and U.S. car measurements quote 0\u201360 miles/hour and 1/4 mile times while European car measurements quote 0\u2013100 kilometers/hour and 400 meter times (which translate to 0\u201396.5606 kilometers/hour and 402.336 meter times, or to 0\u201362.1371 miles/hour and 1/4.02336 mile times, respectively)}} {{efn-lr|name=Variability|Some measurements exclude an initial \"[[rollout (drag racing)|rollout]]\",<ref name=motor-trend-testing>{{cite web|url=http://www.motortrend.com/news/motor-trend-testing/ |title=Testing, Testing - The Motor Trend Way |date=13 March 2008 |work=[[Motor Trend]] |accessdate=8 August 2016 |quote=We subtract a one-foot rollout from the launch to simulate dragstrip performance |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807173553/http://www.motortrend.com/news/motor-trend-testing/ |archivedate=7 August 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> which according to ''Car and Driver'' \"can affect the elapsed time by as much as 0.3 second\".<ref name=CDrollout>{{cite web|url=http://www.caranddriver.com/features/the-importance-of-rollout |title=The Importance of 'Rollout' - Feature - Car and Driver |date=May 2005 |accessdate=21 April 2016 |work=[[Car and Driver]] |last=Webster |first=Larry |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160428155215/http://www.caranddriver.com/features/the-importance-of-rollout |archivedate=28 April 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> Furthermore, environmental conditions change how fast the car drives (tires, surface of testing track, elevation above sea level, weight of the driver, and equipment used for testing are all critical). Times sourced for example by ''Car and Driver'', are modified artificially using computer software after the drive test is complete, to theoretically account for how the car would have performed differently given different weather conditions.<ref name=CDweather>{{cite web|url=http://www.caranddriver.com/features/correcting-for-weather|title=Correcting for Weather - Feature - Car and Driver|date=May 2005|accessdate=12 April 2016|work=Car and Driver|last=Webster|first=Larry}}</ref>}} Tires, elevation above sea level, weight of the driver, testing equipment, weather conditions and surface of testing track all influence these times.<ref name=CDweather/>\nOne-foot [[rollout (drag racing)|rollout]] before the timer starts is industry standard in North America so measurements which exclude the first foot of acceleration are allowed. After [[Car and Driver]] switched to one-foot rollout in 2019 they updated some previous times (about 0.1 second faster than the approximation in the original tests).<ref name=motor-trend-testing/><ref name=CDrollout/><ref name=\"CDrollout2\">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.caranddriver.com/features/a30085446/acceleration-testing-procedure-change-rollout/ |title=We're Making a Slight Change to Our Acceleration-Testing Procedure |first=Dave |last=Vanderwerp |magazine=Car and Driver |location=US |date=5 December 2019 |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" <!--separate columns for 60mph and 100kmh?-->\n!Car{{efn-lr|name=Car|Car models similar to an already mentioned model but differentiated only by minor package options (for example \"convertible editions\") are omitted acknowledging that speed results with those editions can be only slightly less fast. In the case of a tie between two cars, since there exist a variety of different opinions regarding the interpretation of, for example, 1/4 mile trap speed results, the car shown first is the one with the earlier model year (of the fast time's represented model, and not necessarily of any driven car) or if both years are the same it goes to the car having the earliest date associated with the performance data's verification or publishing.}}\n!Model Year{{efn-lr|name=Year|This is the earliest [[model year]] of the car that can claim all its following listed data. This is not necessarily the model year of any driven car, the year when testing was performed, the year during which owners took first delivery of the model, the year it was unveiled, or when it was built.}}\n!Time{{efn-lr|name=Result|This is the fastest result provided by independent sources or the manufacturer.}}\n!{{nowrap begin}}Independent time{{nowrap end}}{{efn-lr|name=Ind. result|This is the fastest result provided by independent sources.}}\n!{{nowrap begin}}Manufacturer time{{nowrap end}}{{efn-lr|name=Man. result|This is the result claimed by the manufacturer.}}\n!Noted specs{{efn-lr|name=Noted specs|These cars usually have, unless otherwise stated, some combination of 2 seats and a [[forced induction]] gasoline mid-engine. Some are produced in limited number (associated with an increase in [[Market value|value]]), and those limited production numbers, if any, are stated.}}\n|-\n|[[Porsche 918 Spyder]]{{efn-lr|name=AWD|all-wheel drive}}\n|2015\n|{{nts|2.1}} sec\n|{{nts|2.1}} sec<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.caranddriver.com/features/g30083537/quickest-cars-of-the-decade/?slide=21 |title=The Quickest Cars of the Decade (with 1-foot rollout) |first=Connor |last=Hoffman |date=7 December 2019 |access-date=16 January 2020 |work=Car and Driver}}</ref><ref name=\"918 Spyder 1\">{{cite web|url=http://media.caranddriver.com/files/2015-porsche-918-spyder-feature-car-and-driver2015-porsche-918-spyder.pdf|title=2015-porsche-918-spyder-feature-car-and-driver2015-porsche-918-spyder.pdf|date=15 May 2014|accessdate=11 April 2016|work=Car and Driver|last=Colwell|first=K.C.}}</ref><ref name=\"918 Spyder 2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.caranddriver.com/features/the-2015-porsche-918-spyder-is-the-quickest-road-car-in-the-world-feature|title=The 2015 Porsche 918 Spyder Is the Quickest Road Car in the World \u2013 Feature \u2013 Car and Driver|date=July 2014|accessdate=11 April 2016|work=Car and Driver|last=Colwell|first=K.C.}}</ref>\n|{{nts|2.5}} sec<ref>{{cite web|url=https://presse.porsche.de/presskits_until_2015/products/2013/spyder/text/technical_data/TD%20918%20Spyder/TD_918_Spyder_Fahrvorstellung_EN5.pdf|title=Specifications of the Porsche 918 Spyder|accessdate=11 April 2016|publisher=[[Porsche]]}}</ref>\n|{{nowrap begin}}Limited to 918 produced, [[Hybrid electric vehicle|hybrid-electric]], [[Naturally aspirated engine|naturally aspirated]]{{nowrap end}}\n|-\n|[[Dodge Challenger#SRT Demon|Dodge Challenger SRT Demon]]\n|2018\n|{{nts|2.1}} sec{{efn-lr|name=Conditions|factory claim with [[rollout (drag racing)|rollout]]; factory claim without rollout is 2.3 sec}}\n|n/a{{efn-lr|name=26s|2.6 sec measured by ''Road & Track'' using Dodge equipment}}\n|{{nts|2.1}} sec<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedrive.com/news/9536/the-dodge-challenger-demon-actually-does-0-60-mph-in-2-1-seconds/ |title=The Dodge Challenger Demon Actually Does 0-60 MPH in 2.1 |publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotrod.com/articles/every-detail-9-second-dodge-srt-demon|title=It\u2019s Here! EVERY Detail On The 9-Second Dodge SRT Demon! |first=Johnny |last=Hunkins |work=Hot Rod Network |location=US |date=11 April 2017 |access-date=17 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.motortrend.com/cars/dodge/challenger/2018/2018-dodge-challenger-srt-demon-first-drive-review/|title=2018 DODGE CHALLENGER SRT DEMON FIRST DRIVE|work=Motor Trend|access-date=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n|Limited to 3300 produced, [[Front-engine, front-wheel-drive layout|front-engine]], with 1(+4) seats\n|-\n|[[Tesla Model S]] P100D w/Ludicrous+ Update{{efn-lr|name=AWD sedan|all-wheel drive, sedan}}\n|2020{{efn-lr|name=P100D|Tesla vehicles don\u2019t have traditional model years per se in the sense of design revisions being pushed out annually. For Tesla, the \"model year\" of any given car is the same as the calendar year that the car was produced but changes and updates, both in hardware and software, are pushed out whenever they are deemed ready. That said, for the purposes of this list, the \"earliest model year of the car that can claim all its following listed data\" (as per the note at the top of the \"Year\" column) is technically 2020 for the Model S P100D and the Model X P100D. No modification by either professional tuners or individuals is necessary.}}\n|{{nts|2.28}} sec\n|{{nts|2.28}} sec{{efn-lr|name=Motor Trend's conditions|Time includes rollout; time without [[rollout (drag racing)|rollout]] is 2.53 sec<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.motorauthority.com/news/1110019_dodge-demon-can-actually-do-0-60-mph-in-2-1-seconds-but-theres-a-catch |title=Dodge Demon can actually do 0-60 mph in 2.1 seconds, but there's a catch |first=Joel |last=Feder |work=Motor Authority |location=US |date=20 April 2017 |access-date=30 September 2018}}</ref>}}<ref name=\"Motor Trend\">{{cite web|url=http://www.motortrend.com/cars/tesla/model-s/2017/2017-tesla-model-s-p100d-first-test-review/|title=2017 TESLA MODEL S P100D FIRST TEST: A NEW RECORD \u2014 0-60 MPH IN 2.28 SECONDS!|last=Brantley|first=Brian|date=7 February 2017|work=Motor Trend|accessdate=7 February 2017}}</ref>\n|{{nts|2.3}} sec<ref name=\"Tesla updates Model S Performance 0-60 mph acceleration to 2.3 seconds\">{{cite web|url=https://electrek.co/2020/04/21/tesla-updates-model-s-performance-acceleration-0-60-mph-2-3-seconds/}}</ref>\n|[[Battery electric vehicle|All-electric]], with 5(+2) seats\n|-\n|[[Ariel Atom#Ariel Atom 500|Ariel Atom 500 (V8)]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arielna.com/arielatom/ |title=Introduction to the Ariel Atom|publisher=Ariel |location=North America |access-date=15 October 2018}}</ref>\n|2008\n|{{nts|2.3}} sec\n|n/a\n|{{nts|2.3}} sec<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.evo.co.uk/ariel/atom/11329/ariel-atom-500-v8 |title=Ariel Atom 500 V8 |first=Ollie |last=Marriage |work=Evo |location=UK |date=6 September 2010 |access-date=30 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arielmotor.co.uk/ariel/history/ |title=History |publisher=Ariel Motor Co |access-date=15 October 2018}}</ref>\n|Limited to 25 produced\n|-\n|[[Lamborghini Hurac\u00e1n#Hurac\