{"title_page": "Eric Christian Olsen", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{BLP sources|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image = Eric Christian Olsen - Monte-Carlo Television Festival (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Olsen in 2013\n| birth_name = Eric Christian Olsen\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1977|5|31|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Morehead, Kentucky]], U.S.\n| occupation = Actor, producer\n| children = 2\n| yearsactive = 1997\u2013present\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Sarah Wright]]|2012}}\n| relatives = [[Daniela Ruah]] (sister-in-law)\n}}\n'''Eric Christian Olsen''' (born May 31, 1977) is an American [[actor]] and [[Film producer|producer]]. He is known for his portrayals of [[Marty Deeks|Detective Marty Deeks]] on the [[CBS]] television series ''[[NCIS: Los Angeles]]'', and of Austin in the film ''[[Not Another Teen Movie]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nOlsen was born in [[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]], [[Oregon]], the son of Jeanne (n\u00e9e Donstad), a [[Non-denominational Christianity|non-denominational]] [[chaplain]], and Paul V. Olsen, a professor of English, and head track and cross country coach of [[Augustana College (Illinois)|Augustana College]] in [[Rock Island, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/85/Eric-Christian-Olsen.html |title=Eric Christian Olsen Biography (1977?-) |publisher=Filmreference.com |date=1977-05-31 |accessdate=2011-08-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.augustana.edu/x12424.xml|title=Coach Paul V. Olsen - Augustana College|website=www.augustana.edu|access-date=2011-10-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014153354/http://www.augustana.edu/x12424.xml|archive-date=2013-10-14|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>[http://www.augustana.edu/alumni/olsen-scholarship-story Augustana.edu] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014152523/http://www.augustana.edu/alumni/olsen-scholarship-story |date=2013-10-14 }}</ref> He has an older brother, David, who acts as his stunt double; David is married to actress and Olsen's ''[[NCIS: Los Angeles]]'' costar [[Daniela Ruah]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/tv/153707_eric_christian_olsen_and_daniela_ruah_talk_densi_relationship_on_ncis_la_could_there_be_wedding_bells|title='NCIS: LA' Stars Eric Christian Olsen and Daniela Ruah on Densi: Could There Be Wedding Bells?|publisher=}}</ref> Olsen is of Norwegian descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/eric-christian-olsen-interview-the-thing-on-set-interview/|title=Eric Christian Olsen On Set Interview THE THING|date=8 October 2010|publisher=}}</ref> Olsen spent most of his childhood in [[Bettendorf, Iowa]] and attended Bettendorf Middle and High School, where he pursued interests such as [[sports]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], and [[Chinese language|Chinese]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ovguide.com/eric-christian-olsen-9202a8c04000641f800000000092a6b4|title=Ovguide.com|access-date=2014-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140312213120/http://www.ovguide.com/eric-christian-olsen-9202a8c04000641f800000000092a6b4|archive-date=2014-03-12|url-status=dead}}</ref>   In addition to many local theatre performances, Olsen trained in improv with [[ComedySportz]] Quad Cities and later joined the cast.\n\n==Career==\nOlsen's first starring role was the titular role in the 1999 TV movie ''Arthur's Quest'', soon after he gave an Emmy submitted portrayal of a dying burn victim on NBC's ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]''. His next role was a small one in HBO's ''Black Cat Run''. Eric soon landed a starring role in the Fox TV series ''[[Get Real (U.S. TV series)|Get Real]]'', playing Cameron Green. The series lasted for a year before Eric made his transition onto the big screen when he played Ben Affleck's gunner in ''[[Pearl Harbor (film)|Pearl Harbor]]'', that was quickly followed by a leading role as Austin \"The Cocky Blond Guy\" in the teen send up feature film ''[[Not Another Teen Movie]]''.\n\nOlsen next played Jake in the teen comedy ''[[The Hot Chick]]''.  In 2003, he won the role of Lloyd Christmas in ''[[Dumb and Dumberer: When Harry Met Lloyd]]'', the prequel to the hit movie ''[[Dumb and Dumber]]''.  Olsen followed that up by playing opposite [[Chris Evans (actor)|Chris Evans]] for a second time in ''[[Cellular (film)|Cellular]]''.  He starred in the yet to be released ''Mojave'' and then joined the final season of Fox's ''[[Tru Calling]]''. He claimed three highly contrasting roles in 2006 and 2007 with the release of ''[[Beerfest]]'', ''[[License to Wed]]'' and Zach Braff's ''[[The Last Kiss (2006 film)|The Last Kiss]]''.\n\nOlsen co-starred as Sully in the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] sitcom ''[[The Loop (U.S. TV series)|The Loop]]''. Olsen had four other projects in 2008 and continues to reside in Malibu, California.\n\nOlsen appeared on [[Will Ferrell]] and [[Adam McKay]]'s streaming video website [[Funny or Die]], with a small series of segments featuring a character called Perry Hilton, a parody of [[Paris Hilton]]. He starred in the 2011 science-fiction horror film ''[[The Thing (2011 film)|The Thing]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Creepy |first=Uncle |url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/38027/finally-we-know-when-we-can-see-the-thing |title=Finally We Know When We Can See The Thing! |publisher=Dreadcentral.com |date=2010-06-15 |accessdate=2011-08-11}}</ref>\n\nOlsen portrays [[Marty Deeks|Detective Marty Deeks]] on the [[CBS]] show ''[[NCIS: Los Angeles]]''. His character appeared in two episodes of season one before joining the cast as a series regular in the second season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/NCISLA-Eric-Christian-Olsen-1021060.aspx|title=NCIS: Los Angeles Promotes Eric Christian Olsen to Series Regular|publisher=[[TV Guide]]}}</ref>\n\nHe is a part of the cast of Mortal Enemy Audio Book by Nicholas Ryan Howard from 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mortalenemybook.com/#the-audio-experience|title=Mortal Enemy Book the Audio Experience|publisher=mortalenemybook.com}}</ref>\n\nOlsen is a producer of a short film \"Bald\" from 2014 and executive producer of a documentary \"Andy Irons: Kissed by God\" from 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.torresurso.com/baldmovie|title=Bald movie|publisher=Torresurso.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tetongravity.com/video/surf/actor-eric-christian-olsen-on-andy-irons-kissed-by-god|title=Andy Irons Kissed by God|publisher=Tetongravity.com|date=August 31, 2018}}</ref>. He has his own [[production company]] Cloud Nine Productions. In 2019 he started his first show as an executive producer picked up in production for Hulu called \"Woke\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/woke-comedy-starring-lamorne-morris-picked-up-to-series-hulu-1202704257/|title=\u2018Woke\u2019 Comedy Starring Lamorne Morris Picked Up To Series By Hulu|publisher=Deadline.com|date=August 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOlsen made his writing debut with the season 11 episode 10 (the 250th overall episode) of [[NCIS: Los Angeles]] titled \"Mother\", which aired December 1, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cartermatt.com/386304/ncis-los-angeles-250th-episode-co-written-by-eric-christian-olsen/|title=NCIS: Los Angeles 250th episode co-written by Eric Christian Olsen!|publisher=Cartermatt.com|date=November 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/ncis-los-angeles-eric-christian-olsen-first-script-hetty-linda-hunt.html/|title=\u2018NCIS: Los Angeles\u2019: Eric Christian Olsen Writes His First Script for the Series and Hetty Is in Trouble|publisher=Showbiz Cheat Sheet|date=November 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOlsen became engaged to actress [[Sarah Wright]] in October 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news/actor-olsen-is-engaged_1252595|title=Actor Olsen Is Engaged|date=October 25, 2011|publisher=ContactMusic|accessdate=April 11, 2012}}</ref> They were married near [[Jackson Hole]], [[Wyoming]], on June 23, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20606709,00.html|title=Eric Christian Olsen Marries Sarah Wright|date=June 25, 2012|author=Monica Rizzo|publisher=People.com|accessdate=June 25, 2012}}</ref>  Their first child, a son, Wyatt Oliver Wright Olsen was born on August 16, 2013 and their second child, a daughter,  Esm\u00e9 Olivia Wright Olsen was born on August 9, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|author=Rizzo, Monica |url=http://celebritybabies.people.com/2013/08/26/eric-christian-olsen-sarah-wright-welcome-son-wyatt-oliver/ |title=Eric Christian Olsen and Sarah Wright Welcome Son Wyatt Oliver |date=26 August 2013 |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/745252/eric-christian-olsen-sarah-wright-olsen-expecting-baby-no-2-and-reveal-pregnancy-with-sweet-photo|title=Eric Christian Olsen & Sarah Wright Olsen Expecting Baby No. 2|website=E! Online|language=en-US|access-date=2016-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://celebritybabies.people.com/2016/08/11/eric-christian-olsen-sarah-wright-olsen-welcome-daughter-esme-olivia/|accessdate=21 October 2016|publisher=People.com|title=Eric Christian and Sarah Wright Olsen Welcome Daughter}}</ref>  Olsen and Wright were featured in a 2015 episode of the [[HGTV]] series ''[[House Hunters]]'' buying a vacation home near Jackson Hole.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.etonline.com/tv/157069_ncis_la_star_eric_christian_olsen_and_wife_sarah_wright_hunt_for_homes_on_hgtv/|title = \u2018NCIS: LA\u2019 Star Eric Christian Olsen and Wife Sarah Wright Hunt for Homes on HGTV|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> Olsen works with the charity [[Hats Off for Cancer]] as an Honorary Board Member and Spokesperson, featured on their Public Service Announcement video.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hats Off For Cancer Board of Directors|url=http://hatsoffforcancer.org/contact/|website=Hats Off For Cancer|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hats Off For Cancer PSA|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VEIV7W5YlfU|website=YouTube|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref>. He and his wife Sarah are members of Board of Directors of [[Environmental Media Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Board of Directors of Environmental Media Awards|url=https://www.green4ema.org/our-boards|website=Board of Directors|accessdate=October 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Mean People Suck]]''\n|Nick\n|[[Short film]]\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Pearl Harbor (film)|Pearl Harbor]]''\n|Gunner\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Not Another Teen Movie]]''\n|Austin\n|\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Local Boys]]''\n|Randy Dobson\n|\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[The Hot Chick]]''\n|Jake\n|\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[Dumb and Dumberer: When Harry Met Lloyd]]''\n|Lloyd Christmas\n|\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Cellular (film)|Cellular]]''\n|Chad Thompson\n|\n|-\n|2004\n|''Death Valley''\n|Josh\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Beerfest]]''\n|Gunther\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[The Last Kiss (2006 film)|The Last Kiss]]''\n|Kenny\n|\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[License to Wed]]''\n|Carlisle Myers\n|\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[The Comebacks]]''\n|Foreign Exchange Student\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Sunshine Cleaning]]''\n|Randy Clever\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Eagle Eye]]''\n|Craig Bolston\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Fired Up (film)|Fired Up]]''\n|Nick Brady\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[The Six Wives of Henry Lefay]]''\n|Lloyd Wiggins\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[The Back-Up Plan]]''\n|Clive Bennett\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[The Thing (2011 film)|The Thing]]''\n|Adam Finch\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Celeste and Jesse Forever]]''\n|Steve Tucker\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''Warning Labels''\n|Thad\n|[[Short film]]\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Band of Robbers]]''\n|Sid Sawyer\n|\n|-\n|2016\n| ''The Relationtrip''\n| Chippy (voice)\n| \n|-\n|2017\n| ''[[Sun Dogs (2017 film)|Sun Dogs]]''\n| Thad\n| \n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Battle of the Sexes (2017 film)|Battle of the Sexes]]''\n|Lornie Kuhle\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''The Place of No Words''\n|\n|